\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Iconic Moments and Exchanges\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Since the scripts are copyrighted, here are detailed descriptions of his most memorable dialogue moments:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 "I love you but you are not serious people"
\f1\b0  Perhaps his most devastating line in the entire series, delivered to his children at a critical moment. It is the thesis statement of his relationship with them -- there is love, but it is entirely conditional on a standard they will never fully meet in his eyes.\

\f0\b On Kendall throughout the series
\f1\b0  Logan's push-pull with Kendall is the emotional spine of the show. He alternates between genuine pride and surgical humiliation, sometimes within the same conversation. His acknowledgment that Kendall might have what it takes -- delivered and then immediately retracted -- is one of the cruelest and most human things the show does.\

\f0\b "Can't make a Tomlette without breaking some Greggs"
\f1\b0  A deliberately mangled phrase that he delivers with total confidence. It reveals his comfort with chaos and his contempt for the people caught in it.\

\f0\b His phone calls
\f1\b0  Logan conducts most of his real business on the phone, often while barely paying attention. The casualness with which he discusses life-altering decisions is consistently chilling.\

\f0\b Addressing his staff and employees
\f1\b0  He has a recurring habit of addressing rooms full of people as though they are mildly inconvenient furniture. His praise, when it comes, lands hard precisely because it is so rare.\

\f0\b The "No" scene
\f1\b0  Logan's ability to end an entire negotiation, argument, or emotional plea with a single flat refusal is one of the show's recurring devices. He does not explain the no. He does not soften it. It simply is.\

\f0\b Late season vulnerability
\f1\b0  In the later seasons, there are flashes -- brief, almost immediately suppressed -- where Logan seems aware of what he has cost himself. These moments are devastating precisely because they are so quickly armored over again.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 His Relationship With Each Child\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Kendall
\f1\b0  -- the one he sees the most of himself in, which is precisely why the relationship is so brutal. Closest to the throne, most psychologically destroyed by proximity to it.\

\f0\b Siobhan
\f1\b0  -- he respects her sharpness but consistently underestimates or sidelines her, partly out of genuine bias and partly because her independence threatens him.\

\f0\b Roman
\f1\b0  -- the dynamic is the most overtly cruel, with genuine affection buried under relentless mockery. Roman is the one who most openly craves Logan's approval and suffers most visibly for it.\

\f0\b Connor
\f1\b0  -- largely ignored, which is its own form of damage. Logan seems to regard him as a disappointment so settled it no longer requires attention.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
